FEMALE CANNABIS PLANTS

Feminized Cannabis Seeds

Feminized cannabis seeds are specially bred seeds that are genetically modified to produce only female plants. In cannabis cultivation, female plants are highly desirable because they produce flowers that contain the highest concentrations of cannabinoids like THC (tetrahydrocannabinol) and CBD (cannabidiol), which are the primary compounds used for both medicinal and recreational purposes. Why Feminized Cannabis Seeds? In a typical batch of regular cannabis seeds, about 50% will grow into male plants, and the other 50% will grow into female plants. Male plants are not desirable for most growers because they do not produce significant amounts of cannabinoids and, if left in the same growing area, can pollinate the female plants. When female plants are pollinated, they produce seeds instead of large, resinous buds, which lowers the overall quality and yield of the crop. Feminized seeds are created by stressing plants to become hermaphrodites that produce pollen. This pollen is then used to fertilize other female plants, resulting in seeds that carry only female chromosomes (XX). Almost all resulting plants will be female because no male chromosomes (XY) are involved.

Growing Feminized

Benefits of Feminized Seeds

Feminized cannabis plants will start flowering once the light schedule changes from 18 hours of light and six dark to 12 hours of light and 12 hours of dark. If growing outdoors, this occurs naturally when the long days begin to be shorter, but it can be done manually indoors by changing the light settings. Higher Yield: Growers can maximize their yield of cannabinoid-rich buds without the risk of accidental pollination. Efficiency: Feminized cannabis seeds are 99.9% guaranteed to cultivate female cannabis plants on germination. Consistency: Feminized seeds offer a more predictable and consistent growing experience, which is particularly important for commercial growers. While feminized seeds are popular, they may only be ideal for some situations. For breeders looking to create new strains, regular seeds (which produce both male and female plants) are necessary to cross-pollinate and develop new genetic varieties.
